PB420 is derived from C. briggsae Gujarat, the strain that later was named G16 and then AF16. PB420 was frozen (as C. briggsae Gujarat) 22 March 1991, thawed 15 June 2020 and sent to the CGC 1 July 2020. It may be considered ancestral to AF16 and was renamed to distinguish it from AF16 strains that have been maintained in laboratory cultures. Reference: Fodor A, et al. Nematologica 1983 92: 203-217. doi:10/1163.187529283X00456 This strain is within four to five generations of the original thaw.

substrate_comments: C. briggsae Isolated by Michael Ailion from rotting apricot from home of Wayne Davis and Danielle Endres in Salt Lake City, Utah, 8/4/2006, under tree on north side of house. Coordinates: 40 42' 26.16"" N, 111 52' 3.27"" W. Animals move very rapidly. Strain started from a single L4 hermaphrodite and grown three generations before freezing. 18S rDNA sequence differs from C. briggsae NCBI entry (PB102), but is identical to the 18S sequence of AF16, HK104, PB800 and VT847. Cross-fertile with AF16.
notes: isolated from rotting apricot from home of wayne davis, 8/4/2006. under tree on north side of house, 40.7073 N, 111.8675 W. hermaphroditic species that closely resembles Caenorhabditis. moves more rapidly than C. elegans and does not interbreed with N2 or CB4856 males. generation time similar to C. elegans. strain started from a single hermaphrodite and grown three generations before freezing. 18S rRNA sequence indicates that it is in the "elegans" group but is not one of the known species. It is C. briggsae. by mating and by 18S sequence (database had incorrect briggsae sequence).

substrate_comments: new hermaphroditic Caenorhabditis species (see EG4181). this "strain" consists of a mix of the worms that came from the apricot to try to maintain as much diversity as possible in the population and thus is not a true strain in the traditional sense. it will be submitted as contaminated worms since it cannot be cleaned up without going through a bottleneck.

substrate_comments: wild isolate from rotten jack fruit collected 4/29/09 by Michael Ailion from near Dois Rios, Ilha Grande, Brazil (-23.18234;-44.19456). many animals of various stages emerged from the fruit, but strain was started from a single L4. the rotten samples that gave strains EG5612-EG5614 all were in the same bag during transport from Brazil, so there is a possibility that these strains are not independent and all came from the same fruit.

Does not form cross-progeny when mated to N2 males. forms cross-progeny when mated with AF16 males.

Isolated from a large fibrous stone fruit rotting underneath the big tree at the head of the Kalalau trail, adjacent to the Ke'e Beach parking area. This strain is derived from a single adult picked from the sample the same day. Same fruit as QG128-9.

substrate_comments: Isolated from a large rotten fruit (unidentified; looks like a baked potato) collected 8/2/09 under the large tree at the trailhead for the Kalalau trail, Ke'e Beach, Kauai, Hawaii. GPS (from google earth) N22°13´12.81´´W159°34´58.67´´. The rinsate from the rotten fruit was put on an agar plate 8/2/09 and picked 4 larvae to a fresh plate immediately. I mailed this plate to NYU and Max chunked picked the worms to NGM with OP50 on 8/13. This strain was bleached prior to freezing on 8/24/09.

substrate_comments: Isolated from a large rotten fruit (same type as QG128-130) collected 8/3/09 from the Kailau Trail, Kauai. GPS N22°04.826´W159°24.746´. The rinsate, on agar plates, contained hermaphroditic Caenorhabditis. I carried chunks of agar to CA and put them on NGM with OP50 in Abby Dernburg's lab, 8/14/09. From the progeny, I singled one worm produce QG132, which was bleached prior to freezing on 8/24/09.

substrate_comments: Isolated from rotten red flowers collected 8/2/09 from near the fence to the west of the women's restroom at the Hanalei Pavilion Beach Park. GPS (from google earth) N22°12´23.51´´W159°29´52.23´´. Same sample as QG122. This strain was founded by one male and one animal I supposed was a female, but the 'cross' gave rise to only hermaphrodite offspring; the male was perhaps the QG122 species. The hermaphrodite offspring were frozen 8/28/09, never having been bleached.
